                        <h3>Flys to Use:</h3>
                        <p>
                            During Spring: 
                        </p>
                        <ul class="list">
                            <li>Woolly Bugger: A versatile streamer pattern imitating various aquatic creatures.</li>
                            <li>Hare's Ear: An effective nymph pattern imitating various aquatic insects.</li>
                            <li>Black Gnat: A versatile fly pattern resembling various insects.</li>
                            <li>Olive Emerger: Mimics emerging olive-colored insects and can be productive during hatches.</li>
                            <li>Greenwell's Glory: Known for imitating various insects, including pale watery duns, during spring hatches.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-md-4 ">
                        <img src="../Images/119.jpg" class="img-fluid w-75" />
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-8 fix">
                        <p>
                            During Summer: 
                        </p>
                        <ul class="list">
                            <li>CDC Emergers: Patterns imitating emerging insects with CDC feathers.</li>
                            <li>Bibio: Resembles beetles, effective when fished near the surface.</li>
                            <li>Invicta: Traditional wet fly pattern effective during summer hatches.</li>
                            <li>Pheasant Tail: Mimics mayfly nymphs and works well in various sizes during hatches.</li>
                            <li>Daddy Longlegs or Cranefly Patterns: Effective for imitating terrestrial insects.</li>
                            <li>Greenwell's Glory: Known for imitating various insects, including pale watery duns, during summer hatches.</li>
                            <li>Pheasant Tail Nymph: Resembles various aquatic insects and works well in summer when trout are feeding sub-surface.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-md-4 ">
                        <img src="../Images/longleg.jpg" class="img-fluid w-75" />
                    </div>
                </div>


                <div class="row">
