                        <p>
                            During Autumn: 
                        </p>
                        <ul class="list">
                            <li>Hoppers: Mimics grasshoppers or terrestrial insects that can fall into the water during this season.</li>
                            <li>Midges: Especially in the latter part of autumn, midges become prevalent, and imitating them with patterns like Griffith's Gnat can be successful.</li>
                            <li>Caddis Nymphs: Mimic caddisfly larvae, which can be prevalent in autumn waters.</li>
                            <li>Muddler Minnow: Continues to be a versatile choice for imitating various baitfish.</li>
                            <li>Sparkle Dun: Mimics mayflies in the emerger stage, effective during hatches.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-md-4 ">
                        <img src="../Images/hopper.jpg" class="img-fluid w-75" />
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-md-8 fix">
                        <p>
                            During Winter: 
                        </p>
                        <ul class="list">
                            <li>Black Stonefly Nymphs: Effective for imitating stonefly nymphs in colder waters.</li>
                            <li>Bloodworm Patterns: Mimics bloodworms, which trout feed on during winter in some waters.</li>
                            <li>Buzzer Patterns: Imitates the larval stage of midges, which can be active in winter.</li>
                            <li>
                                <p>In winter, dry fly fishing tends to be less productive due to decreased insect activity on the surface. However, in moments of warmer weather or during midge hatches, small patterns like Griffith's Gnat can still work.</p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
